After failing to secure a table at another establishment, I was happy to walk find a easy going spot to eat with my two hungry boys. There was a bit of a wait but things moved along quickly and there was a nice bench outside to relax on. We happened to be between breakfast and dinner, the menu was condensed, but there was plenty of staples to choose from, red beans and rice, pó boys, etc... My boys split the fried chicken, and fries and well seasons cooked to perfection and plenty to share. They both approved, especially of the biscuits. My wife and I both had pó boys. I was indecisive, so our server suggested that I go with the half oyster and half shrimp. An excellent suggestion. The oysters were perfectly cooked, which can be a chore, the bun was right on, as was the shredded iceberg and tomato. The remoulade was generous, next time I am going to ask to have that scaled back, but that is a personal preference not reflective of the sandwich. The pickled watermelon rinds were off the hook, the slaw was nice, and the fresh watermelon sweet tea was a treat - I also appreciated the free refill. And the beignets, I can be a purist so I was a bit skeptical of the Ghirardelli chocolate filled version, be it was masterfully pulled off and were the originals. I am looking forward to exploring this menu a bit.

My boyfriend and I took a day trip to SF from san jose and we were told to try Brenda's, especially for their crawfish beignet. Down in orange county, the first beignet i've ever tried was from disneyland, their classic powdered sugar beignet, so when hearing about this amazing crawfish beignet, I didn't know what to expect. When you come in, you write your name on a chalkboard and the host will call you based on availability of table and how many chairs there are at specific tables. It took about 45 minutes for us to get a table, but as i was looking around, everyone got some sort of beignet, so I knew i was in for a treat. When we finally sat down we decided on the Shrimp gumbo and a flight of beignets that included: powder, chocolate, crawfish, and apple crisp. First off, the shrimp gumbo was delicious. It may be just me, but i love when food has a lot of contrasting flavors that just work, and yes, this gumbo DID work. It was definitely very savory, with a little bit of spice in it. The plate was also a little cheesy with texture, but not to the taste. I read reviews of Brenda's before deciding what to order, and this gumbo definitely didn't disappoint. I was cautious when i went to try the crawfish beignet because I honestly did not know what to expect. There was sprinkled spice on the top of it too but i could smell the savory-ness without even cutting into it. I can't even describe the taste. All i can say is that I WANT MORE. You would expect it to be spicy or have a kick, but it was actually very savory and delicious. The fluff of the beignet added to the center and brought the whole beignet together. The chocolate beignet was a little sweet for me, and of course the powdered one was as expected. The apple crisp was good as well, but I can't get over how delicious the crawfish beignet was. I don't know what they do to make the beignet itself, but whatever they're doing, they're doing it well.

There were limited vegan options here, but the atmosphere was good. I'm sure it's be good for meat eaters

Incredible food and service! It is Cajun food- but with a twist. For example, they offer crawfish beignets as an appetizer, and Ghirardelli chocolate and apple beignets for dessert. Our waiter (didn't get his name-tall, thin, maybe Hispanic) was so helpful! He gave the right suggestions for dishes and made ordering between all the amazing dishes easier. Highlights: The red beans and rice! The watermelon rinds which was an interesting touch Get the glazed yams ($4) as a side. They were buttery and sweet. I cannot wait to go back!

Brenda, Brenda, Brenda! That food was so delicious!! The wait was long but after reading the reviews and reviewing the menu I knew that the wait would be well worth it! After about 45 minutes we were sat with the attentive server Louis and he knew exactly how to help us! After devouring delicious Granny Smith beignets, I received my beautiful bowl of shrimp and grits! The entire meal was executed beautifully with the shrimp cooked to perfection!! I've never had soul food, BUT, I love French food, I love brunches, i love teatime, and basically any type of meal you can have throughout the day. Depending on the day of the week and the time you come, Brenda's can definitely satisfy all the options I mentioned above. My first experience was 2 weeks ago at the odd hour of 3:30. Thanks to the World Cup, I was eating on really odd schedules. Anyway, the + side of things was that there was no wait. Our party of 4 got seated immediately. Shrimp & Grits- super decadent, rich, and full of flavor. Be warned, this dish is pretty heavy, I doubt that I would be able to clean the whole plate myself, definitely wouldn't want to anyway because I would love to save room for other items. Beignet Flight- awesome, my favorites of the sampler were...ALL OF THEM!! I can't say I prefer plain or savory or sweet, just gotta order them all. Not trying to sound glutinous or anything. Cornmeal fried oyster po'boy- not my cup of tea. There's absolutely nothing wrong with it but I don't like eating cooked oysters. It was alright according Dad, not the best. I regret not getting catfish or the shrimp version. Peanut butter ice box pie- this is heavenly. The pie itself was delicious and highly recommended by our waitress. It was served pretty cold, to the point where it seems like you're eating ice cream, but you know it's not ice cream. Loved it. Definitely would recommend it if you're a Reese's Pieces or peanut butter lover. Overall, I loved my first experience @ Brenda's and would come back for brunch or dinner, or even this (3-5pm) "tea time" hour. The waitress was slightly cold at first but warmed up towards the end of the meal, hmmm I wonder why? ;) Side notes: Special menu items (such as the peanut butter ice box pie) had to be ordered only exactly at 5, they're NOT served in the in-between hours. Also, your whole party has to be there before the restaurant seats you (during peak hrs.) according to my lovely mother who frequently comes here with coworkers.

This place was so good. Had to wait in line for an hour at 10:00 on a Saturday morning but it was well worth it. The dishes have so much flavor and everything is Cajun style. Got to try the benedicts and the po boys. Wanted to try the pork belly and grits but did not have the room. I will def be back.

    My boyfriend and I took a day trip to SF from san jose and we were told to try Brenda's, especially for their crawfish beignet. Down in orange county, the first beignet i've ever tried was from disneyland, their classic powdered sugar beignet, so when hearing about this amazing crawfish beignet, I didn't know what to expect.

    When you come in, you write your name on a chalkboard and the host will call you based on availability of table and how many chairs there are at specific tables. It took about 45 minutes for us to get a table, but as i was looking around, everyone got some sort of beignet, so I knew i was in for a treat.

    When we finally sat down we decided on the Shrimp gumbo and a flight of beignets that included: powder, chocolate, crawfish, and apple crisp.

    First off, the shrimp gumbo was delicious. It may be just me, but i love when food has a lot of contrasting flavors that just work, and yes, this gumbo DID work. It was definitely very savory, with a little bit of spice in it. The plate was also a little cheesy with texture, but not to the taste. I read reviews of Brenda's before deciding what to order, and this gumbo definitely didn't disappoint.

    I was cautious when i went to try the crawfish beignet because I honestly did not know what to expect. There was sprinkled spice on the top of it too but i could smell the savory-ness without even cutting into it.

    I can't even describe the taste. All i can say is that I WANT MORE. You would expect it to be spicy or have a kick, but it was actually very savory and delicious. The fluff of the beignet added to the center and brought the whole beignet together.

    The chocolate beignet was a little sweet for me, and of course the powdered one was as expected. The apple crisp was good as well, but I can't get over how delicious the crawfish beignet was. I don't know what they do to make the beignet itself, but whatever they're doing, they're doing it well.

    7/15/2014

    1 check-in

    I've never had soul food, BUT, I love French food, I love brunches, i love teatime, and basically any type of meal you can have throughout the day.  Depending on the day of the week and the time you come, Brenda's can definitely satisfy all the options I mentioned above. My first experience was 2 weeks ago at the odd hour of 3:30. Thanks to the World Cup, I was eating on really odd schedules. Anyway, the + side of things was that there was no wait. Our party of 4 got seated immediately.

    Shrimp & Grits- super decadent, rich, and full of flavor. Be warned, this dish is pretty heavy, I doubt that I would be able to clean the whole plate myself, definitely wouldn't want to anyway because I would love to save room for other items.

    Beignet Flight- awesome, my favorites of the sampler were...ALL OF THEM!! I can't say I prefer plain or savory or sweet, just gotta order them all. Not trying to sound glutinous or anything.

    Cornmeal fried oyster po'boy- not my cup of tea. There's absolutely nothing wrong with it but I don't like eating cooked oysters. It was alright according Dad, not the best. I regret not getting catfish or the shrimp version.

    Peanut butter ice box pie- this is heavenly. The pie itself was delicious and highly recommended by our waitress. It was served pretty cold, to the point where it seems like you're eating ice cream, but you know it's not ice cream. Loved it. Definitely would recommend it if you're a Reese's Pieces or peanut butter lover.

    Overall, I loved my first experience @ Brenda's and would come back for brunch or dinner, or even this (3-5pm) "tea time" hour.  The waitress was slightly cold at first but warmed up towards the end of the meal, hmmm I wonder why? ;)

    Side notes: Special menu items (such as the peanut butter ice box pie) had to be ordered only exactly at 5, they're NOT served in the in-between hours. Also, your whole party has to be there before the restaurant seats you (during peak hrs.) according to my lovely mother who frequently comes here with coworkers.
